(The Dirac distributions on) $s_0$ and $s_1$ are distinguishable and there is a formula for the expected stopping time of the SPRT due to Wald --REF--.

\begin{equation*}
\EE_{s_1}[N_{\alpha, \beta}] = \frac{\beta \ln \frac{1 - \alpha}{\beta} + (1 - \beta) \ln(\frac{\alpha}{1 - \beta})}{\psi \ln \frac{\phi}{\psi} + (1 - \psi)\ln \frac{1 - \phi}{1 - \psi}}.
\end{equation*}

This formula uses the fact that the differences $\ln L_n - \ln L_{n-1}$ are independent. Further the denominator $\psi \ln \frac{\phi}{\psi} + (1 - \psi)\ln \frac{1 - \phi}{1 - \psi} = \EE_{s_1}[\ln L_n - \ln L_{n-1}]$ which is the average slope of $\ln L_n$. In the general case $\ln L_n - \ln L_{n-1}$ are not independent but in the limit as $n \rightarrow \infty$ we have the following result.
\begin{restatable}{theorem}{liexplimits}\label{liexplimits}
Let $(Q, \Sigma, \Psi)$ be an HMM and let $\pi_1, \pi_2$ be initial distributions. Then $\liexp$ converges $\pi_2$-almost surely to at most $|Q|^2$ values $\Lambda = \{l_1, \dots, l_K\}$ in the set $[-\infty, 0]$.
\end{restatable}



Although it is not known by the authors if an explicit formula for the expected time of the SPRT exists in the general case, the following relationship exists in the limit between the likelihood exponent and $N$ in the case $\alpha = \beta \rightarrow 0$. We write $N_\alpha$ in place of $N_{\alpha, \alpha}$. 

